    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A pitot tube works by measuring the difference between the static air pressure and the dynamic air pressure. The static port, usually located on the side of the aircraft, measures the static air pressure, while the pitot tube, pointing straight ahead, measures the dynamic air pressure. The difference between these two pressures gives the airspeed indicator the necessary information.\n\nWhen the opening of the pitot tube gets blocked, it can no longer accurately measure the dynamic air pressure, leading to incorrect airspeed readings. This can be a significant issue as it may cause the pilot to make incorrect decisions based on faulty information. In the worst-case scenario, it could lead to aerodynamic stall or even an accident. That's why it's crucial to keep the pitot tube clear of any obstructions. Remember, even the smallest blockage can lead to a big problem, just like a single misplaced cobblestone can cause a whole road to crumble.",
      "source": "target",
